ḥanna is a form phonetically associated with the “gahawah syndrome” typical of the nomadic dialects of Northern Arabia. The semi-nomadic tribes of the area make use of both forms, ḥənna and ʔəḥna, which are felt to be stylistic variants. Thus, ḥənna is preferred in narrative style and in intertribal communication when visiting tribes which use it
ʔəḥna is preferred when visiting the tribes having that form
